<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="324" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[174,1378,2376,3470]" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">
<emphasis box="[176,868,3201,3234]" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
There have been some observations on Lesson’s Saddle-back Tamarin near Mocoa on the Rio 
<collectingRegion box="[1008,1123,3240,3273]" country="Colombia" name="Caqueta" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Caqueta</collectingRegion>
and on an island in the Rio Guineo, 
<collectingRegion box="[464,607,3283,3312]" country="Colombia" name="Putumayo" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Putumayo</collectingRegion>
. They are found in groups of 5-10 individuals. They have been observed traveling with Goeldi’s Monkey (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1904" box="[940,1161,3318,3351]" class="Mammalia" family="Callitrichidae" genus="Callimico" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="19" pageNumber="324" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="goeldii">Callimico goeldii</taxonomicName>
). A population survey in floodplain forest near the Quebradon el Ayo, 
<collectingCountry box="[969,1107,3357,3390]" name="Colombia" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, a small clearwater tributary south of the Rio 
<collectingRegion box="[549,664,3397,3430]" country="Colombia" name="Caqueta" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Caqueta</collectingRegion>
near the Brazilian border, found 16-9 ind/km* or 3 groups/km?®.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="324" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="19.[1441,2648,288,676]" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">
<emphasis box="[1442,1788,288,321]" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
CITES Appendix II. Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red Last (as S. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spix" authorityYear="1823" box="[1638,1763,327,360]" class="Mammalia" family="Callitrichidae" genus="Saguinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="19" pageNumber="324" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fuscicollis">fuscicollis</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1840" box="[1767,1856,327,360]" class="Mammalia" family="Callitrichidae" genus="Saguinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="19" pageNumber="324" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fuscus">fuscus</taxonomicName>
). Lesson’s Saddle-back Tamarin is widespread and common. Although hunted to some extent for food and for pets,it is not threatened.Its status in 
<collectingCountry box="[1572,1650,406,439]" name="Brazil" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Brazil</collectingCountry>
is unknown. The Juami-Japura Ecological Station and the Mamiraua Sustainable Development Area are within its supposed geographic distribution in 
<collectingCountry name="Brazil" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, but its presence there has not been confirmed. In 
<collectingCountry box="[2212,2350,492,517]" name="Colombia" pageId="19" pageNumber="324">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, it occurs in La Paya and Cahuinari national natural parks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
